00:01.520 --> 00:09.860
First of all, your origins as a writer, it seems to me that you could have
probably gone either way, back either mainstream or science fiction, like, oh,

00:09.940 --> 00:20.640
back in the mid-60s, the first two novels I've located of yours, the Solarians
and the Men in the Jungle. Yeah, Solarians was science fiction, and the Men in

00:20.640 --> 00:30.420
the Jungle was not, correct? Wrong. Oh, Men in the Jungle is? Yes! Oh, okay,
okay, I didn't find the book. I just read somebody who said it was. No, it's a

00:30.420 --> 00:41.780
science fiction novel. It has a lot of relevance to Vietnam and stuff like that
was going on at the time, but it is a science fiction novel. It's not

00:41.780 --> 00:50.280
the same kind of hardcore science fiction that Solaronis is. It takes place on
another planet and everything, but it's a political science fiction novel. Okay,

00:50.400 --> 00:58.260
my question would still have some validity, though. I was going to ask, you must
have wondered whether you should pick up science fiction or whether you should

00:58.260 --> 01:06.940
go into the so-called mainstream. Was that ever a choice you made? Well, I have
actually written three mainstream novels, two of which have been published.

01:07.580 --> 01:17.780
Right. One is the Passing Through the Flame, which was a novel about, among
other things, drug smuggling Hollywood, the record business, movies. And another

01:17.780 --> 01:25.600
one, which is a current one this year, is called The Mind Game, which is about
cults. Then there's a third book called The Children of Hamelin, which was

01:25.600 --> 01:36.220
written in 69 and published, never published as a book, for various political
reasons. It was serialized in the Los Angeles free press in 28 installments

01:36.220 --> 01:47.220
about 70 or 71, and it's just now going to be published next year by an outfit
called Pequod Press in Los Angeles. It's sort of like resurrecting a book that I

01:47.220 --> 01:56.920
thought I would never sell. It was sold in England, never published. It was
about, it's kind of a historical novel about the origins of the counterculture,

01:57.080 --> 02:06.040
in a way. Yeah, I'd read, excuse me, I'd read references to that that had never
been published. It had never been, it was published in, it was serial, the

02:06.040 --> 02:15.500
serialization was published. And, you know, in the free press, which is a big
underground newspaper, a quarter of a million people read it, in pieces or more,

02:15.680 --> 02:25.240
but for various reasons I thought publisher would touch it until now, which is
being done by a small press. Yeah. Well, no, I knew you'd written mainstream

02:25.240 --> 02:32.960
fiction, obviously, but it never has come down to a choice then as to which you
were. Only on each individual. I mean, you know, on each individual book, it

02:32.960 --> 02:42.580
comes down to a choice. Well, I'm sure I will continue to write science fiction
novels. I'm sure I will also continue to write mainstream novels. Just depends

02:42.580 --> 02:54.620
on... And I usually never can plan, want to plan, or do plan, more than one book
ahead. So whatever the next thing I come up with is the novel I do. And

02:54.620 --> 03:04.460
sometimes it's science fiction, sometimes it isn't. So what I've actually
written is seven science fiction novels and three mainstream novels. Okay. One

03:04.460 --> 03:16.660
of your earlier ones, The Agent of Chaos, was that probably your first
successful novel? I mean depends what you mean by success reputation sales well

03:16.660 --> 03:27.740
not much in sales it's a very strange book that book it was published originally
by an author called Belmont about which the less said the better it's never been

03:27.740 --> 03:35.880
out of print yeah go ahead it's never been out of print it's never had a
tremendous number of printing but it's in all what has had a lot of political

03:35.880 --> 03:44.480
effect and has created various movements down through the years still continuing
to do so and i don't even know all of uh the ramifications of what it's created

03:45.100 --> 03:56.240
uh created you know it was uh the inspiration for the zippies for the pie kill
movement uh for certain political groups in europe and now there's another group

03:56.240 --> 04:05.260
in washington that i just got in contact with which called itself something for
paradoxical politics which also uses that book so i guess that was uh the first

04:05.260 --> 04:15.080
book that had that kind of uh social political impact I thought it was, compared
to some of your other work, I thought it was fairly traditional in style and

04:15.080 --> 04:26.280
plot. It had the good guys and the bad guys. At the end, there was the hope of
alien contact and the betterment of humanity and so forth. I'd heard it called

04:26.280 --> 04:34.940
an underground classic on college campuses and so forth. Well, that's why it's
called an underground classic, because it was involved and inspired a lot of

04:34.940 --> 04:43.180
counter-cultural political movements. Which uses it manual. But also, I have
heard from various people that it's a popular book in prisons.

04:45.760 --> 04:57.500
Okay, Book Jack Barron, I guess, is one of your better-known books. I thought
that Jack was a little different type of hero than most of you others. He's more

04:57.500 --> 05:06.020
of an anti-hero, a wenching, cursing, power-hungry kind of individual. To me,
that was very non-traditional, maybe even a little shocking for a normal science

05:06.020 --> 05:15.940
fiction reader. Did you mean for the book and Jack to shock people? Well, there
are two diverse reactions to the character of Jack Barron. One is that he's an

05:15.940 --> 05:30.200
anti-hero, and the other is that he is a hero. What I was trying to do with the
character of Barron, among other things, was... For me, Barron is not an anti

05:30.200 --> 05:40.300
-hero. Darren is a guy who's involved with power, but he has an ambivalent
feeling about it. In other words, he has a sense of personal irony about his own

05:40.300 --> 05:49.940
desires for power. And as the book opens, he's become a TV star because he wants
to get out of chasing after power and just wants to be a star. Then he gets

05:49.940 --> 06:01.580
pulled back into it by a Van Sant Sinon. Actually, what I was trying to do in a
way, the book has a very traditional plot, As far as I was concerned, it has a

06:01.580 --> 06:11.140
positive hero, it has a negative villain, the hero wins, the villain loses, all
that stuff that is considered the traditional way of plotting a book, and yet

06:11.140 --> 06:21.460
it's written in a different kind of way. It kind of takes that superficial kind
of plot and treats it in a realistic manner, which confused a lot of people, I

06:21.460 --> 06:30.740
think. What was the flap in the parliament about that novel? Yeah, that novel
had a lot of trouble. It was written under contract to Doubleday, who then

06:30.740 --> 06:39.680
rejected it. You have to remember the political climate of the era. They didn't
reject it. They said, we'll publish it if you cut out all the sex, all the swear

06:39.680 --> 06:50.700
words, and all the politics, which is the whole book. So it took a long time to
resell that book here. In the meantime, I took it to Milford, to a Milford

06:50.700 --> 06:57.520
conference, and Mike Moorcock was there. And he read it and he like it and he
serialized it in New World. So his first publication was actually in England in

06:57.520 --> 07:07.340
the magazine. Now, halfway through the serialization, I forget exactly which
part, part three, part four, W.A. Smith, which was the biggest distributor,

07:07.500 --> 07:15.640
still is the biggest distributor in England, refused to distribute the magazine
because of the book in it. Now, at that time, New World had an arts council

07:15.640 --> 07:25.820
grant. The arts council is an organ of the British government. Now, the Arts
Council supported the magazine against Smith publicly. But the flap in

07:25.820 --> 07:34.120
Parliament arose when certain right-wing members of Parliament were aghast that
an organ of the British government, the Arts Council, was defending this kind of

07:34.120 --> 07:44.320
stuff. And that's how it became a parliamentary issue. Okay, I'd always thought
that the British exercised more tolerance. They did! Well, that's the whole

07:44.320 --> 07:52.120
point. In other words, the Arts Council was an organ of the government itself.
And the government successfully fought private censorship in a book. The

07:52.120 --> 08:00.480
government, an organ of the government, in a way, the Arts Council, supported
the freedom of the press and supported the magazine and supported the book. The

08:00.480 --> 08:08.980
people in Parliament who objected to this were right-wing members of Parliament
who were aghast at what the government was doing to preserve free press. So it

08:08.980 --> 08:16.460
doesn't reflect at all badly on the English attitude, or even on the attitude of
the government at the time, just on the attitude of a certain faction in

08:16.460 --> 08:27.720
Parliament who felt that the government shouldn't be acting this way. Okay. One
other question I had on that one. Maybe my reaction to Jack as an antihero was a

08:27.720 --> 08:37.200
little off here, but I saw the book more as a comment on the power of the media
and the power of politics rather than a crusade or a didactic treatise or

08:37.200 --> 08:45.600
something of that sort. Would I be right in that response, do you think? Well,
you'd be right in that. And also, I mean, the book is about power.

08:46.020 --> 08:56.660
It's about power itself is neutral as far as I'm concerned. It's what people do
with it that counts. Barron is a guy who likes power and keeps referring to it

08:56.660 --> 09:06.620
as a drug and knows that he could become addicted to it and for that reason has
decided to stay away from it. Then he gets drawn back into playing with power

09:06.620 --> 09:15.520
because he comes to the conclusion that it's better for somebody who feels that
way about power to be wielding it than people who don't have any self

09:15.520 --> 09:25.440
-consciousness about the dangers of wielding power. So in that sense, it's a
comment on the power of the media, but it's also a comment on the morality of

09:25.440 --> 09:37.060
power, on the paradox of power, which is that if you leave power to be wielded
by people who do not see the dangers, the personal dangers, the psychological

09:37.060 --> 09:47.240
dangers of being involved with it then you end up with people like Benedict
Howitz, Ronald Reagan and Richard Nixon who do not have self-consciousness and

09:47.240 --> 09:55.100
this about the personal dangers, the moral dangers of chasing after power
whereas somebody like Barron, who is certainly an imperfect person as all people

09:55.100 --> 10:10.480
are, at least his saving grace if he has one, is that he is well aware of the
personal dangers of being involved in a quest for power. Okay, good. One thing

10:10.480 --> 10:19.280
I've been impressed about when I was reading through your work is the different
styles that you use. The Iron Dream, I think, is one that particularly

10:19.280 --> 10:28.080
fascinated me. Sturgeon, in the introduction to that book, called it a unique
book, belonging to a category all its own. Did you have fun writing that book?

10:28.180 --> 10:39.640
Was it hard to change your style to sort of write down? Well, except at the end
where I wrote the scholarly demolition of the book. Because in order to write

10:39.640 --> 10:49.940
that book, I had to write like Hitler. And in order to get to that point, I had
to read everything Hitler had written, which is very boring indeed. And I had to

10:49.940 --> 10:56.540
also write a book called Hitler's Dinner Conversations, like 800 pages of
Hitler's babblings at the dinner table, which was taken down to a short end by

10:56.540 --> 11:04.700
Martin Borman, a fascinating book. But in order to write the bulk of that book,
Hitler's novel, inside the book, I had to write like Hitler. I had to get inside

11:04.700 --> 11:13.700
Hitler's head. That was not what I could consider a fun experience. In other
words, it was like playing a role. You had to put yourself inside his head.

11:14.100 --> 11:27.660
Yeah, I call that method writing. Exactly like that. And so it was a very
difficult book to write. Kind of a shattering book to write because of the kind

11:27.660 --> 11:38.480
of position I put myself in. Also, of course, Hitler was a terrible writer. So
in order to be accurate, I really had to write something awful, in a way. Also,

11:38.480 --> 11:45.640
Hitler is getting crazier and crazier as he's writing the book, so I got crazier
and crazier as I was writing the book, which was necessary in order to write the

11:45.640 --> 11:46.380
book in the first one.

11:51.340 --> 11:52.200
We're all in the hand.

11:59.180 --> 12:06.440
that thing? Well, the impetus came from a conversation with Mike Whorcock in
London, where I was living at the time, about how he wrote sword and sorcery,

12:06.560 --> 12:23.500
and how he used Freudian imagery, and the basic appeal of sword and sorcery.
That gave me the idea that if Hitler had not become the fuhrer of Germany, he

12:23.500 --> 12:34.620
could have as well winded up writing sword and sorcery. And I've always been
fascinated with the whole question of how a thing like Nazism could really

12:34.620 --> 12:44.060
happen. And none of the stuff I had read about that really satisfied me,
political or economic or conventional explanations of how this happened. And the

12:44.060 --> 12:51.620
two things came together. And my insight about Nazism was that it was a
psychosexual phenomenon and that Hitler came to power by, in effect,

12:51.720 --> 12:52.940
manipulating imagery

12:55.520 --> 13:05.420
and psychosexual substructures, rather than by a coherent economic program and
so forth. And this has a certain correlation with a certain kind of sword and

13:05.420 --> 13:14.600
sorcery, and that was the basic impetus that generated the book. Has anyone
really misunderstood that book and called you a fascist or anything like that?

13:15.220 --> 13:24.320
Rarely. No, rarely, rarely. Actually, not really. The book is going to be
published in Germany next year I don't know what's going to happen then

13:27.220 --> 13:36.520
No, the only kind of misunderstanding That I read In a review that I really got
Was a little bit different It was somebody who said Well, this is really all

13:36.520 --> 13:42.840
good fun I really enjoyed this book Why did he have to muck it up with all this
stuff about Hitler And all the extraneous paraphernalia It was just a good,

13:42.840 --> 13:54.880
rousing adventure tale Yeah That is the only kind of misreading of the book
that's really taken place. Actually, I have not been called a Nazi or a fascist

13:54.880 --> 14:05.480
by anyone that I know of in connection with that book. After you published that
book, if I'm reading your schedule of writing correctly, from 1972 to about 1979

14:05.480 --> 14:08.560
when you published The World Between, you didn't do any science fiction.

14:12.460 --> 14:27.100
Well, yes and no. I mean, World Between was written about 77 or 78, 77, I guess,
76, 77. And because of various publishing screw-ups, it took a while to come

14:27.100 --> 14:37.380
out. But after I wrote The Iron Dream, my next book was Passing Through the
Flame, which was a very long, mainstream novel. up. Then I actually wrote

14:37.380 --> 14:44.100
another main, see, the schedule, everything was screwed up. I wrote Passing
Through the Flame after the Iron Dream. Then I wrote another mainstream novel

14:44.100 --> 14:53.400
called The Mind Game, which just came out this August due to various publishing
screw-ups. And then I wrote A World Between. So there were two mainstream books

14:53.400 --> 15:01.320
in between in terms of what, you know, which came out in different order, but
that was the order in which they were written. Well, A World Between was the

15:01.320 --> 15:10.860
next science fiction novel, all, though, after the archery that I wrote. I
thought that maybe you'd gotten tired of science fiction or something. No, I

15:10.860 --> 15:22.340
did. I had gotten tired of science fiction a while, and I did write two
mainstream books in between. A rather long ones. Okay, The World Between, again,

15:22.340 --> 15:31.440
I'm not sure of my ground here, but The World Between and Songs from the Stars,
I see those as sort of a different old kind of writing for you, sort of a

15:31.440 --> 15:42.080
mellowing down in Songs from the Stars and the World Between Both the conflict
is between extremes and then you sort of advocate a medial position a grey area

15:42.080 --> 15:51.920
as the proper place to be would that be a correct response to those? I think
that'd be a correct response to A World Between. I'm not so sure about Songs

15:51.920 --> 16:02.620
from the Stars I think again this is all, you know, I guess what I'm getting
into now is books about the fallacy of dualistic thinking and I think that's

16:02.620 --> 16:11.840
part of what Songs from the Stars is more about. Songs from the Stars, I think
the position, you know, the ultimate positive position that is shown is not so

16:11.840 --> 16:25.300
much a position in between the two conflicting signs but one that transcends
both of them that's in a much larger context. I would say in general that up

16:25.300 --> 16:38.320
until I guess the world between really, a lot of my stuff was kind of critical
fiction, critical of this, critical of existing societies, critical of various

16:38.320 --> 16:48.760
things that were going on. A World Between is meant as a utopian novel, really,
in any kind of way. And it's a prescriptive kind of book. It's more of, instead

16:48.760 --> 16:58.320
of presenting critical images of other things, that the idea is to create a more
positive image of a more positive kind of future. I think if you spend enough

16:58.320 --> 17:11.380
time when criticizing what exists, at some point you have some kind of moral
obligation to present something more positive and replace what you find

17:11.380 --> 17:21.180
negative. Yeah, that's maybe the way I should have said it instead of mellowing.
Yeah, I recognize for the first time I can see you advocating some things rather

17:21.180 --> 17:31.360
than criticizing. Okay. In the world between, would you say that Carlotta and
Royce would describe your, I guess your ideal male-female relationship, equality

17:31.360 --> 17:37.320
and all that? Well, yes and no. It's a relationship that evolves in the book.

17:41.420 --> 17:51.480
In other words, the problem with writing a utopian novel is being too grammatic
about it, being too black and white about it, having all the positive characters

17:51.480 --> 18:00.320
be all positive, having what you want to show is a positive relationship, being
a perfect relationship and I don't think I was trying not to do that there the

18:00.320 --> 18:08.500
way it comes out that way and I think that is a positive relationship but I
would want to say that it's perfect I mean in the beginning of the book it's a

18:08.500 --> 18:25.440
little bit of a reverse a subtle kind of reverse of present things in other
words Royce is subtly a little downtrodden in the beginning and sort of gains a

18:25.440 --> 18:37.140
truer and less superficial equality as the book progresses. Okay, the Institute
for Transcendental Science obviously is one of the extremes in the book. Where

18:37.140 --> 18:51.100
would you say their error was exactly? Well, I think... Well, their error...
That's a complicated question. But I think basically there are two areas of

18:51.100 --> 19:04.340
error in transcendental science. One is the unexamined, subtle male chauvinist
bias to their culture, and the other one is the ultimate conviction that what

19:04.340 --> 19:16.600
they are doing is the absolute most important thing in the universe, and that
therefore they are morally entitled to run over other people's cultures and

19:16.600 --> 19:30.240
desires. Absolutism I guess would be, even the kind of theocratic absolutism
would be their flaw. Not the Faustian thing at all because I do see Faust as a

19:30.240 --> 19:43.220
hero. Okay. Every once in a while I detect in your work a tendency to identify a
character or movement with an actual person. Was I correct in picking out the

19:43.220 --> 19:58.620
name Shockley as the founder of that thing? that was meant as a... Well, it was
thrown in there, but it wasn't meant as a direct reference

19:58.620 --> 20:11.940
to Sean Lin. However, you know, you can read that stuff into there. I don't
know. In another book, I named a character after the wolfman in that movie. Now

20:11.940 --> 20:22.580
I can't remember his name. But it was a subconscious thing that I did. I don't
think that wasn't a direct reference really. Okay, the femocrats in that book,

20:22.660 --> 20:34.740
the femocracy, do you get any feedback from Women's Lib on something like that?
The strange thing about the reaction to that book has been that a certain number

20:34.740 --> 20:46.460
of men have reacted in a kind of male liberal guilt, male feminist kind of
reaction against that. for the most part, women have liked the book. Women have

20:46.460 --> 20:56.600
identified with it more than men. Actually, I even got one or two good reviews
in feminist places. I think that's not quite what I expected, but that seems to

20:56.600 --> 21:04.820
be the way it happened. I have not gotten heavy feminist from that. A little
bit, but not much. Not much, because I think women who are involved in feminism

21:05.280 --> 21:15.940
or have been or know women who are, can recognize a certain aspect a certain
aspect of the feminist movement in the Femocrats. Whereas men who are trying to

21:15.940 --> 21:25.880
show how liberated they are would not dream of admitting such a thing. Whereas
women have had experience with that kind of mentality. Strangely enough. I

21:25.880 --> 21:35.080
didn't expect the reaction to be that way. I expected it to be reversed, but
that's not the way it was. Okay. I'd like to move on to Songs from the Stars. We

21:35.080 --> 21:43.040
fortunately got a hold of a copy of that. That guy you put us on to, John
Douglas, sent one. Just a personal response, first of all. I think that's a

21:43.040 --> 21:50.760
Nebula book. I think it deserves the award. One never knows what wins the
Nebulas. Well, I don't know what your response to an award like that is anyhow,

21:50.880 --> 22:01.180
but I was... Well, you know, my response to an award like that is it's nice to
get awards and you make money by being able to put awards on your books, but you

22:01.180 --> 22:10.900
see what's won and what hasn't. You can't take it as a very serious literary
judgment. Anyway, just from my personal standpoint I thought it was your best

22:10.900 --> 22:21.120
novel. The way I read this, you said a few words about it before, but it was
almost to me a plea for people to join hands, to meet the challenge of the

22:21.120 --> 22:30.560
future. You have almost a fairy tale with a hero, a heroine, a world in danger,
alien contact, the future hanging in the balance. Did you mean to echo those

22:30.560 --> 22:40.840
kinds of traditional themes? Make it that kind of a story? Well, I don't know.
No, I think that's

22:40.840 --> 22:48.320
exactly what I was trying to do. It's not good to ask writers what they're
trying to do in that sense, because any book that's any good, you're really

22:48.320 --> 23:03.160
writing it half out of your subconscious, and you're not planning every aspect
of everything, thematic aspect of what people later read into it. Again, it's a

23:03.160 --> 23:07.400
book against duality. You have two fragmented societies, they're both...

23:10.260 --> 23:21.580
Both are kind of like half societies. The Aquarian society there is a very nice
thing that works, except it really only works because it accepts something from

23:21.580 --> 23:32.080
the black scientists which it doesn't want to admit that it's accepting. And the
black scientists are, again, another kind of absolutism

23:34.960 --> 23:49.540
which doesn't sell it. It's a book about higher unity, I guess, rather than that
the conflict is really superficial. And it mirrors the present thing in our

23:49.540 --> 23:56.920
society where on the one hand you have a great big space movement and people
wanting to get into space and all the old people and all that stuff. On the

23:56.920 --> 24:08.520
other hand, you have a real atavistic neoludite movement, an anti-nuclear
movement, which is really kind of willfully ignorant of a lot of things. In a

24:08.520 --> 24:12.020
way, these are the two things that could bring about the crash,

24:15.560 --> 24:25.860
as well as what would survive it. So I think it's basically a book about the
grand philosophical attempt of that book is to try and bridge the gap between

24:25.860 --> 24:37.980
science and reason and feeling, emotion, and mysticism. and to... you know, to
point to a higher unity between the two things, and away from the false

24:37.980 --> 24:46.680
dichotomies and false dualisms, which seem to be really destroying western
civilization. That's a large statement. Okay, yeah, yeah, I can accept that. The

24:46.680 --> 24:57.120
higher unity you talk about, I would relate that somehow, the way that Clear,
Blue, Lew follows, and the songs that represent alien contact, he sort of blends

24:57.120 --> 25:06.740
his way, the earthly one, into a sort of a galactic one. Yeah. Do you think
we're going to meet helpful creatures like the aliens in that book that you...

25:06.740 --> 25:15.820
Well, yes, as I said in the book, I do believe that any civilization that's
going to last a million years, it's going to be a million years or whatever or

25:15.820 --> 25:24.600
even 100,000 years more advanced than us. They've been around that much longer
and that much more advanced science. If it's going to survive to that length of

25:24.600 --> 25:33.620
its own history, it's got to solve it. It's got to be, by that time,
philosophically and emotionally pretty together or long since it destroyed

25:33.620 --> 25:48.940
itself. We certainly will not survive a million years of our own history if it
continues as it has. Obviously not. I think the idea that advanced aliens can be

25:48.940 --> 26:02.080
malignant is very dubious. Are you following what I'm saying? Yes. That any
civilization that survives a million years of its own history has had to have

26:02.080 --> 26:16.260
gotten its political, psychological, and philosophical act together. And I don't
see why. I, you know, and I do believe that if and when we run into that kind of

26:16.260 --> 26:25.680
really advanced civilizations, that they will, if not be directly actively
helpful, certainly will be benign and will not be interested in either eating us

26:25.680 --> 26:33.700
or conquering our planet or blowing us up or anything like that. Okay, David
needs to stop it. Okay.

